{{distinguish|Asháninka language}} {{Infobox language |name=Ashéninka |altname=Campa |states=Peru, Brazil |ethnicity=[[Ashéninka people]] |speakers=9,881 |date = 2017 |ref=<ref name=BDPIO>{{cite web |title=Base de Datos Oficial de Pueblos Indígenas u Originarios |url=http://bdpi.cultura.gob.pe/node/103#main-content |website=Base de Datos de Pueblos Indígenas u Originarios |publisher=Ministerio de Cultura del Perú}}</ref> |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Arawakan languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Campa languages|Campa]] |lc5=cjo |ld5=Pajonal |lc6=cpy |ld6=South Ucayali |lc2=cpu |ld2=Pichis |lc4=cpb |ld4=Ucayali-Yurúa |lc1=prq |ld1=Perené |lc3=cpc |ld3=Apurucayali |glotto=asha1242 |glottoname=Ashe-Asha Norte, Asheninka |glottorefname=Asheninka }} Ashéninka (Ashéninca, Ashéninga) is the name that some [[Variety (linguistics)|varieties]] included in the Ashéninka-Asháninka [[Dialect continuum|dialect complex]] have traditionally received, which belongs to the [[Campa languages|Kampan]] branch of the [[Arawakan languages|Arawak]] family<ref name=Pedrós2018>{{cite journal |last1=Pedrós |first1=Toni |title=Ashéninka y asháninka: ¿de cuántas lenguas hablamos? |journal=Cadernos de etnolingüística |date=2018 |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=1-30 |url=http://www.etnolinguistica.org/article:vol6n1p1-30 |accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>. The [[Ethnologue]] distinguishes seven languages throughout the whole complex, while Pedrós<ref name=Pedrós2018/> proposes a division in three languages (Ashéninka, [[Asháninka]] and Northern Ashé-Ashá) based on the principle of mutual intelligibility. The varieties included in Ashéninka and Northern Ashé-Ashá have traditionally been called ''Ashéninka''. The Glottolog reflects Pedrós’ proposal, although considering the languages proposed by him as groupings of the languages that the Ethnologue distinguishes.
According to the indigenous peoples database of the Peruvian Ministry of Education,<ref name=BDPIO/> there are 13,496 people living in Ashéninka communities, of whom 9,881 (73%) claim to be able to speak the language. The Ethnologue gives much higher figures for the different Ashéninka varieties.
The classification of the different varieties was first established by David Payne in his Apurucayali Axininca grammar,<ref name=Payne1981>{{cite book|last1=Payne|first1=David L.|title=The Phonology and Morphology of Axininca Campa|date=1981|publisher=Summer Institute of Linguistics|location=Dallas}}</ref> but he referred to them as dialects and not as different languages.<ref name=Payne1981/>{{rp|3–5}}
Ashéninka is a locally official language in Peru, as are all [[Languages of Peru|native Peruvian languages]]. It and its relatives are also known by the largely pejorative term ''Campa''.
== Alphabet == Ashéninka was recognized as a separate language from Asháninka in 2017, and the process to fix an alphabet was underway during 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Urpia participará del primer taller de normalización del alfabeto Ashéninka |url=https://www.gacetaucayalina.com/2018/04/urpia-participara-del-primer-taller-de-normalizacion-del-alfabeto-asheninka-1.html |accessdate=6 September 2018 |publisher=Gaceta Ucayalina |date=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Minedu exhibe alfabetos oficiales y materiales educativos en lenguas originarias |url=https://andina.pe/agencia/noticia-minedu-exhibe-alfabetos-oficiales-y-materiales-educativos-lenguas-originarias-710896.aspx |accessdate=6 September 2018 |agency=Andina. Agencia Peruana de Noticias |date=22 May 2018}}</ref>
